e Britishgovernment cleared the group's $21 billion hostile bid for theconglomerate.   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said Thursday he would not referHoylake's offer to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, upholdingthe Conservative government's free-market policies and sweepingaside concerns about the advent of giant, highly leveraged, junkbond-financed buyouts in Britain.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Koito Manufacturing Co. said it will not give T.Boone Pickens Jr. more power just because the U.S. investor isincreasing his stake in the Japanese auto parts supplier to 26percent.   But the company, which Pickens has railed against for repeatedlyrefusing him a spot on its board of directors, said Thursday hislarger ownership could threaten its position on the Tokyo StockExchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Several major airlines matched an AmericanAirlines initiative that will increase some discount fares by morethan 15 percent and double cancellation penalties.   Under the proposal matched Thursday, the popular ``MaxSaver''cut-rate fare often used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14days in advance, will be increased by $10 to $20 round trip. The``MaxSaver'' tickets will remain non-refundable.   In addition, fares will be raised on seven-day advance tickets by$30 to $60 round trip. The penalty for changing or canceling areservation will double to 50 percent of the ticket price.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas Air Corp., strapped for cash because of thestrike and bankruptcy of its Eastern Airlines subsidiary, isdiscussing the sale of a stake in its computer reservation system toa General Motors Corp. unit, sources said.   Sources close to the situation said Thursday the airline companywas looking for a partner for the reservation subsidiary, calledSystem One.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The total cost of the UAL Corp. buyout could reach$9.45 billion, according to Securities and Exchange Commissionfilings by the employee-managment group seeking to take over UnitedAirlines' parent.   The group, composed of United pilots, UAL's top management andBritish Airways PLC, also announced in newspaper ads Thursday thecommencement of their tender offer for all outstanding shares ofUAL's common stock for $300 a share.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leaders of the U.S. meatpacking industry said theyare exploring new ways to reduce repetitive-motion injuries thatstrike their workers more than those in any other business.   The American Meat Institute, an industry group, is fundingresearch aimed at detecting the early warning signs of carpal tunnelsyndrome, the most severe of the disorders, the organization'spresident said Thursday.   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration levied heavyfines against several meatpackers in recent years for violating lawsaimed at preventing repetitive-motion injuries.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market posted a small loss for the second straightsession Thursday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closedwith a 3.61 point loss at 2,680.28.   The dollar gained ground against the major currencies in quietdealings. Gold prices were unchanged to slightly higher.   Bond prices fell slightly.   Grain and soybean futures prices rallied strongly; silver futureswere sharply higher; oil futures were mixed; and livestock and meatfutures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>